al |url=https://www.medicare.gov/hospitalcompare/profile.html#ID=390236 |website=www.medicare.gov |publisher=U.S. Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services |accessdate=29 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nMemorial Hospital started out on April 5, 1925, when Mrs. Hila C. Mills, a nurse, opened the two bed Mills [[Maternity]] and Convalescent Home on South Street. The first year she had 56 maternity and other medical cases. By 1934 her residence was no longer large enough and she put on an addition, with the home becoming a licensed 21 bed hospital the following year. In 1936, she purchased the house next door as an addition to the hospital. It soon became known as Mills Community Hospital.<ref name=HMD>{{cite news |title=Hila Mills Dies; Founder of Community Hospital |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/towanda-daily-review-jan-27-1975-p-3/ |accessdate=29 May 2019 |work=The Daily Review, Towanda, Pa. |date=27 Jan 1975 |page=3 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1959, Memorial Hospital, Inc. was formed and it opened a new 42 bed [[acute care]] hospital in its present location.<ref name=\"HVFM2018\">{{cite web |title=Heritage Village and Farm Museum Guide 2018 Edition |url=http://mansfieldpennysaver.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/HVFM-GUIDE-2018.pdf |website=Mansfield Penny Saver |publisher=The Bradford County Heritage Association |accessdate=29 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=HMD /><ref name=TPS1>{{cite news |title=The End of an Era: Memorial Hospital\u2019s Maternity Center |url=http://www.troypennysaver.com/PS/2013/09/30/the-end-of-an-era-memorial-hospitals-maternity-center/ |accessdate=29 May 2019 |work=Troy Pennysaver |date=30 September 2013}}</ref> Ten years later, the hospital added an [[labor ward|obstetrical suite]], [[x-ray]] department, patient room wing, and an [[emergency room]]. In 1974, a four-bed [[intensive care unit]] was added, along with a [[skilled nursing facility]].<ref name=\"Official\">{{cite web |title=Guthrie Towanda Memorial Hospital, PA |url=https://www.guthrie.org/location/guthrie-towanda-memorial-hospital |website=www.guthrie.org |publisher=Guthrie |accessdate=29 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn Sept. 20, 2013, the maternity ward closed due to a decline in the numbers of births at the hospital leading to financial struggles.<ref name=TPS1 /> In 2015, Memorial Hospital joined [[Guthrie Robert Packer Hospital|Guthrie]] leading to the change in name to Guthrie Towanda Memorial Hospital.<ref name=TPS2>{{cite news |title=Guthrie and Memorial Hospital affiliation to take place April 1 |url=http://www.troypennysaver.com/PS/2015/03/03/guthrie-and-memorial-hospital-affiliation-to-take-place-april-1/ |accessdate=29 May 2019 |work=Troy Pennysaver |date=3 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe hospital received the [[Women's Choice Awards|Women's Choice Award]] for Emergency Care in 2017 and 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=Guthrie Towanda Memorial Hospital Receives Women's Choice Award\u00ae for Emergency Care |url=https://www.guthrie.org/press-releases/guthrie-towanda-memorial-hospital-receives-womens-choice-award%C2%AE-emergency-care |accessdate=29 May 2019 |publisher=Guthrie |date=15 Mar 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Guthrie}}\n\n{{Hospital-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1925]]\n[[Category:1925 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in Pennsylvania]]\n{{authority control}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox hospital\n<!-- All parameters and comments should be left intact for future editors -->\n<!-- All parameters are optional, but please copy the entire template -->\n<!-- Full documentation: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Infobox_hospital -->\n| name        = Guthrie Towanda Memorial Hospital\n| org/group   = Guthrie\n| logo        = Guthrie_logo.svg\n| logo_size   = <!-- logo size or width in pixels -->\n| image       = <!-- preferably photo of the main building or entrance -->\n| image_size  = <!-- 220 is the default image size or width in pixels (225 matches default map_size). Leave blank per [[MOS:ACCESSIBILITY]] unless special size is needed. -->\n| alt         = <!-- alternative text for image, see [[WP:ALT]] -->\n| caption     = <!-- text displayed below image -->\n| map_type    = <!-- uses the [[Template:Location map]] format; defines value for {{{1}}} parameter; must have latitude and longitude if using this -->\n| relief      = <!-- any non-blank value (yes, 1, etc.) will cause the template to display a relief map image, where available -->\n| map_size    = <!-- map size or width in pixels (do not include \"px\"); default is 225 -->\n| map_alt     = <!-- alternative text for map image, see WP:ALT for details -->\n| map_caption = <!-- a small caption under the map such as \"Shown in region, country\" -->\n| mapframe-zoom = 5\n| location    = 91 Hospital Drive<!-- optional \u2013 displayed before region, state, country -->\n| region      = [[Towanda, Pennsylvania|Towanda]]<!-- e.g. City or County -->\n| state       = [[Pennsylvania]]<!-- optional \u2013 UK: England, Wales, Scotland, Northern Ireland; US: the US state name; CA: province name -->\n| country     = US<!-- country name or two-letter code \u2013 use UK for United Kingdom or US for United States -->\n| coordinates = {{coord|41|47|02.9|N|76|26|54.7|W|display=inline, title}}<!-- Use {{coord}} template with 'display=inline, title' -->\n| healthcare  = Private<!-- UK: NHS; AU/CA: Medicare; ELSE free-form text, e.g. Private -->\n| funding     = Non-profit<!-- use: Non-profit, For-profit, Government, Public \u2013 will generate links -->\n| type        = Community<!-- use: Community, District, General, District General, Teaching, Specialist -->\n| religious_affiliation = <!-- religion the hospital is associated with -->\n| affiliation = <!-- medical school / university affiliations (medical or paramedical) -->\n| patron      = <!-- the individual who acts as the hospital patron -->\n| network     = <!-- hospital network, non-owner -->\n| standards   = <!-- optional if no national standards -->\n| emergency   = <!-- UK/IR/HK/SG: Yes/No, in CA/IL/US: I/II/III/IV/V for Trauma certification level -->\n| beds        = 35<!-- cite in article as well -->\n| speciality  = <!-- if devoted to a speciality (i.e. not a broad spectrum); ONLY displayed if type=Specialist or type=Teaching -->\n| helipad     = {{Airport codes|||5PN2}}<!-- [[Template:Airport codes]] with p=n; leave blank if unknown or not verifiable -->\n| h1-number   = H1<!-- The designation of the helipad (up to h12) -->\n| h1-length-f = 50<!-- Helipad length in feet -->\n| h1-length-m = 15<!-- Helipad length in metres -->\n| h1-surface  = Concrete<!-- Helipad surface type, such as: Concrete, Asphalt, etc -->\n| founded     = 1925<!-- cite in article as well -->\n| closed      = <!-- if defunct, please also add to Category:Defunct hospitals -->\n| demolished  = <!-- if demolished at a different time from closure -->\n| website     = {{URL|www.guthrie.org/location/guthrie-towanda-memorial-hospital}}\n| other_links = <!-- link(s) to related articles -->\n| module      = <!-- or 'embedded' or 'nrhp' -->\n}}\nThe '''Guthrie Towanda Memorial Hospital''' (formerly known as '''Memorial Hospital''') is a 35-bed community hospital in [[Towanda, Pennsylvania]].<ref name=\"CMS\">{{cite web |title=Hospital Compare: Guthrie Towanda Memorial Hospital |url=https://www.medicare.gov/hospitalcompare/profile.html#ID=390236 |website=www.medicare.gov |publisher=U.S. Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services |accessdate=29 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nMemorial Hospital started out on April 5, 1925, when Mrs. Hila C. Mills, a nurse, opened the two bed Mills [[Maternity]] and Convalescent Home on South Street. The first year she had 56 maternity and other medical cases. By 1934 her residence was no longer large enough and she put on an addition, with the home becoming a licensed 21 bed hospital the following year. In 1936, she purchased the house next door as an addition to the hospital. It soon became known as Mills Community Hospital.<ref name=HMD>{{cite news |title=Hila Mills Dies; Founder of Community Hospital |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/towanda-daily-review-jan-27-1975-p-3/ |accessdate=29 May 2019 |work=The Daily Review, Towanda, Pa. |date=27 Jan 1975 |page=3 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1959, Memorial Hospital, Inc. was formed and it opened a new 42 bed [[acute care]] hospital in its present location.<ref name=\"HVFM2018\">{{cite web |title=Heritage Village and Farm Museum Guide 2018 Edition |url=http://mansfieldpennysaver.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/HVFM-GUIDE-2018.pdf |website=Mansfield Penny Saver |publisher=The Bradford County Heritage Association |accessdate=29 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=HMD /><ref name=TPS1>{{cite news |title=The End of an Era: Memorial Hospital\u2019s Maternity Center |url=http://www.troypennysaver.com/PS/2013/09/30/the-end-of-an-era-memorial-hospitals-maternity-center/ |accessdate=29 May 2019 |work=Troy Pennysaver |date=30 September 2013}}</ref> Ten years later, the hospital added an [[labor ward|obstetrical suite]], [[x-ray]] department, patient room wing, and an [[emergency room]]. In 1974, a four-bed [[intensive care unit]] was added, along with a [[skilled nursing facility]].<ref name=\"Official\">{{cite web |title=Guthrie Towanda Memorial Hospital, PA |url=https://www.guthrie.org/location/guthrie-towanda-memorial-hospital |website=www.guthrie.org |publisher=Guthrie |accessdate=29 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn Sept. 20, 2013, the maternity ward closed due to a decline in the numbers of births at the hospital leading to financial struggles.<ref name=TPS1 /> In 2015, Memorial Hospital joined [[Guthrie Robert Packer Hospital|Guthrie]] leading to the change in name to Guthrie Towanda Memorial Hospital.<ref name=TPS2>{{cite news |title=Guthrie and Memorial Hospital affiliation to take place April 1 |url=http://www.troypennysaver.com/PS/2015/03/03/guthrie-and-memorial-hospital-affiliation-to-take-place-april-1/ |accessdate=29 May 2019 |work=Troy Pennysaver |date=3 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe hospital received the [[Women's Choice Awards|Women's Choice Award]] for Emergency Care in 2017 and 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title=Guthrie Towanda Memorial Hospital Receives Women's Choice Award\u00ae for Emergency Care |url=https://www.guthrie.org/press-releases/guthrie-towanda-memorial-hospital-receives-womens-choice-award%C2%AE-emergency-care |accessdate=29 May 2019 |publisher=Guthrie |date=15 Mar 2018}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Guthrie}}\n\n{{Hospital-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1925]]\n[[Category:1925 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in Pennsylvania]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guthrie_Towanda_Memorial_Hospital"}
{"title_page": "Volbeat", "text_new": "{{short description|Danish rock band}}\n{{About|the Danish rock band|the fictional creature|List of generation III Pok\u00e9mon#Volbeat}}\n{{EngvarB|date=March 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Volbeat\n| image               = Volbeat - Rock Am Ring 2016 - Leonhard Kreissig 201606RAR16VOL0017.jpg\n| caption             = Volbeat in 2016. L\u2013R: [[Rob Caggiano]], [[Michael Poulsen]], [[Jon Larsen (Danish musician)|Jon Larsen]], and Kaspar Boye Larsen.\n| landscape           = yes\n| background          = group_or_band\n| origin              = [[Copenhagen]], Denmark\n| genre               = {{flatlist|\n* [[Heavy metal music|Heavy metal]]\n* [[hard rock]]\n* [[psychobilly]]\n* [[rockabilly]]\n* {{nowrap|[[groove metal]]}}\n* [[rock and roll]]\n}}\n| years_active        = 2001\u2013present\n| label               = {{flatlist|\n* Rebel Monster\n* [[Mascot Records|Mascot]]\n* [[Vertigo Records|Vertigo]]\n* [[Universal Records|Universal]]\n* [[Republic Records|Republic]]\n* [[Spinefarm Records|Spinefarm]]\n}}\n| associated_acts     = [[Dominus (band)|Dominus]]\n| website             = {{URL|volbeat.dk}}\n| current_members     = \n* [[Michael Poulsen]]\n* [[Jon Larsen (Danish musician)|Jon Larsen]]\n* [[Rob Caggiano]]\n* Kaspar Boye Larsen\n| past_members        = \n* Teddy Vang\n* [[Franz Gottschalk]]\n* [[Thomas Bredahl]]\n* [[Anders Kj\u00f8lholm]]\n}}\n\n'''Volbeat''' are <!-- Please refer to WP:ENGVAR. This article is written in British English, which uses the plural format while referring to music groups. Volbeat may also refer to a Pok\u00e9mon, but is completely different. Please do NOT change \"are\" to \"is\". Thank you. --> a Danish [[Rock music|rock]] band formed in [[Copenhagen]] in 2001. They play a fusion of [[rock and roll]], heavy metal and [[rockabilly]]. Their current line-up consists of vocalist and guitarist [[Michael Poulsen]], guitarist [[Rob Caggiano]], drummer [[Jon Larsen (Danish musician)|Jon Larsen]] and bassist Kaspar Boye Larsen. The band is signed to Dutch label Mascot Records and has released six studio albums and one DVD. All of their studio albums have been [[Music recording sales certification|certified gold]] in Denmark. Their second album ''[[Rock the Rebel/Metal the Devil]]'' received platinum status, and their 2010 release ''[[Beyond Hell/Above Heaven]]'' was subject to widespread international critical acclaim, receiving double platinum in Denmark, platinum in Finland and Germany, and gold in the United States,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&se=volbeat#search_section|title=Gold & Platinum - RIAA|work=RIAA|access-date=18 March 2017}}</ref> Sweden and Austria. Volbeat's seventh album, ''[[Rewind, Replay, Rebound]]'', was released on 2 August 2019.\n\n==History==\n\n===Early years (2001\u20132004)===\n[[File:Volbeat Michael Poulsen 2009.jpg|thumb|left|Michael Poulsen, singer, guitarist and main songwriter of Volbeat]]\nSinger [[Michael Poulsen]]'s first band was [[death metal]] act [[Dominus (band)|Dominus]].<ref name=\"katt\">{{cite web|url=http://www.katt.com/2014/04/22/jake-daniels-tuesdays-broadcast-4-22-14/|title=Jake Daniels Tuesday\u2019s Broadcast 4-22-14|date=April 22, 2014|accessdate=16 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"allmusic1\">{{cite web|last=True|first=Chris|url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/volbeat-mn0000725175/biography|title=Volbeat Biography|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|date=|accessdate=16 September 2019}}</ref> In 2000, Poulsen became fed up with the death metal music scene, causing Dominus to break up.<ref name=\"allmusic1\"/><ref name=\"katt\"/> In 2001, Poulsen went on to form a new band with some friends and other former Dominus members.<ref name=\"allmusic1\"/> This was the beginning of Volbeat.<ref name=\"allmusic1\"/>\n\nThe band name \"Volbeat\" was derived from Dominus's third album name, ''Vol.Beat'' (read as: Volume Beat).<ref name=\"katt\"/> After selling 1,000 copies of their ''Beat the Meat'' demo tape, Volbeat was signed to a record deal by Rebel Monster Records, a sub-label of Mascot Records.<ref name=\"allmusic1\"/>\n\n===''The Strength / The Sound / The Songs'' (2005\u20132006)===\n\nVolbeat released their first album, [[The Strength/The Sound/The Songs]] in 2005.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Volbeat-The-Strength-The-Sound-The-Songs/release/955581|title=Volbeat - The Strength / The Sound / The Songs|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2017-01-25}}</ref> The line-up for the album consisted of Michael Poulsen (vocals), Jon Larsen (drums), Franz Gottschalk (guitar) and Anders Kj\u00f8lholm (bass).<ref name=\"allmusic1\"/> The album was a huge success in Denmark achieving a spot at No. 18 in the charts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metalstorm.ee/bands/biography.php?band_id=2788&bandname=Volbeat |title=Volbeat - Biography - Metal Storm |publisher=MetalStorm.ee |date= |accessdate=20 February 2010}}</ref> Critics were generally positive towards ''The Strength / The Sound / The Songs''. The German [[hard rock]] magazine RockHard gave it 10/10 in a review.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rockhard.de/index.php?smod=p209Wz1iMUIfo2qAo2D9pz9wn2uupzDhpzI2nJI3pl5xMKEunJkJnJI3Wzqlo3IjFHD9pzuspzI2nJI3WzAioaEyoaEWEQ00ZQV4AlMmqJAbp3ElnJ5aCKMioTWyLKDz |title=Rock Hard Online rockt das Web |publisher=RockHard.de |accessdate=20 February 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927235922/http://www.rockhard.de/index.php?smod=p209Wz1iMUIfo2qAo2D9pz9wn2uupzDhpzI2nJI3pl5xMKEunJkJnJI3Wzqlo3IjFHD9pzuspzI2nJI3WzAioaEyoaEWEQ00ZQV4AlMmqJAbp3ElnJ5aCKMioTWyLKDz |archive-date=27 September 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> [[The Strength / The Sound / The Songs]] also received a handful of awards, including Best Album in the Danish Metal Musik Awards in 2005.<ref name=ansvol>{{cite web|url=http://www.answers.com/topic/volbeat |title=Volbeat: Information from Answers.com |publisher=Answers.com |date= |accessdate=20 February 2010}}</ref> Volbeat was praised for its [[concert|live performance]]s. Their concert at [[Roskilde Festival]] 2006 received a 6/6 stars review in the Danish newspaper [[B.T. (tabloid)|BT]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.last.fm/music/Volbeat |title=Volbeat - Discover music, videos, concerts, & pictures at Last.fm |publisher=Last.fm |date= |accessdate=20 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n[[File:20140613-067-Nova Rock 2014-Volbeat-Anders Kj\u00f8lholm.JPG|thumb|right|upright=0.6|Bassist Anders Kj\u00f8lholm at [[Nova Rock Festival|Nova Rock]] 2014]]\n\n===''Rock the Rebel / Metal the Devil'' (2007)===\n\nThe band, featuring the same line-up as their first album, released their second album, ''[[Rock the Rebel/Metal the Devil]]'', in week 8 of 2007, where it debuted as No. 1 in the Danish Top 40 for CD-sales.<ref name=ansvol />\n\nThey opened the [[Roskilde Festival]] in 2007 and also supported [[Metallica]] together with [[Mnemic]] at their concert in Denmark 13 July of that year.<ref name=\"allmusic1\"/> They were to support [[Megadeth]] in Finland and in their home town, [[Copenhagen]], and to make a few festival appearances mid-2008.<ref name=\"allmusic1\"/> They hired [[Thomas Bredahl]] following the recording of ''Rock the Rebel / Metal the Devil'' as a replacement for Gottschalk on guitar.<ref name=\"allmusic1\"/>\n\n===''Guitar Gangsters & Cadillac Blood'' (2008\u20132009)===\n\nIn 2008, Volbeat released their third album, ''Guitar Gangsters & Cadillac Blood'' featuring guitarist Thomas Bredahl. [[Guitar Gangsters & Cadillac Blood]] topped the Finnish Album Chart straight after its publication.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://yle.fi/lista/listat/tuote.php?id=8898 |title=Suomen virallinen lista |publisher=yle.fi |date= |accessdate=}}</ref> In 2009, Volbeat supported the symphonic metal band [[Nightwish]] on their U.S tour in May.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metalfromfinland.com/news/2008-10-28_23:47/volbeat_to_support_nightwish_on_spring_2009_us_tour |title=Volbeat To Support Nightwish on Spring 2009 U.S. Tour - Metal from Finland |publisher=MetalFromFinland.com |date=28 October 2008 |accessdate=20 February 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120220013008/http://www.metalfromfinland.com/news/2008-10-28_23:47/volbeat_to_support_nightwish_on_spring_2009_us_tour |archive-date=20 February 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> On 31 May 2009 they were on the main stage of the [[Pinkpop Festival]]. They also supported Metallica on the North American leg of Metallica's [[World Magnetic Tour]] from October to December 2009.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metallica.com/index.asp?item=602410 |title=Metallica.com - More Opening Act News |publisher=Metallica.com |date=27 July 2009 |accessdate=20 February 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100125041505/http://www.metallica.com/index.asp?item=602410 |archive-date=25 January 2010 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\nIn 2009 the band played at the biggest open-air festival in Europe (400,000\u2013500,000 rock fans every year), [[Przystanek Woodstock]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.en.wosp.org.pl/woodstock/|title=Home - Wielka Orkiestra \u015awi\u0105tecznej Pomocy|work=Wielka Orkiestra Swi\u0105tecznej Pomocy|accessdate=10 January 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100325213029/http://www.en.wosp.org.pl/woodstock/|archivedate=25 March 2010}}</ref> in Poland.\n\n===''Beyond Hell / Above Heaven'' (2010\u20132012)===\n[[File:20140613-064-Nova_Rock_2014-Volbeat-Michael_Sch\u00f8n_Poulsen_and_Rob_Caggiano.JPG|thumb|right|Rob Caggiano and Michael Poulsen at [[Nova Rock Festival|Nova Rock]] 2014]]\nPoulsen stated about ''[[Beyond Hell/Above Heaven]]'', \"The album title refers to the overall theme of the album, and it continues the storyline from where \"Guitar Gangsters & Cadillac Blood\" left off...\".<ref name=voldk>{{cite web |url=http://volbeat.dk/2010/02/15/volbeat-reveals-album-title/ |title=Volbeat: Official Homepage - Volbeat Reveals Album Title! |publisher=Volbeat.dk |date=15 February 2010 |accessdate=20 February 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100222225514/http://volbeat.dk/2010/02/15/volbeat-reveals-album-title/ |archivedate=22 February 2010  }}</ref>\n\nOn 25 January 2010, it was confirmed that Volbeat would be performing at [[Download Festival]] in June 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rocksound.tv/news/read/download-2010-stage-times-revealed|title=Download 2010 Stage Times Revealed|publisher=Rock Sound|date=8 June 2018|accessdate=16 September 2019}}</ref> It was also confirmed that Volbeat were to join [[Metallica]], [[Megadeth]], [[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]], [[Slayer]] and others in the \"Big Four\" show at Sonisphere Switzerland.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sz.sonispherefestivals.com/2010/01/volbeat-definitiv-bestatigt/ |title=VOLBEAT DEFINITIV BEST\u00c4TIGT: Sonisphere 2010 Switzerland |publisher=SonisphereFestivals.com |date=10 January 2010 |accessdate=20 February 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100724130615/http://sz.sonispherefestivals.com/2010/01/volbeat-definitiv-bestatigt/ |archive-date=24 July 2010 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> It was also announced that the new album, ''Beyond Hell/Above Heaven'' was to be released on 10 September 2010. The band also announced their \"Beyond Hell/Above Heaven Live 2010\" tour.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://volbeat.dk/2010/05/14/album-release-and-fall-dates-confirmed/ |title=Volbeat: Official Homepage - Album release and fall dates confirmed! |publisher=Volbeat.dk |date=14 May 2010 |accessdate=30 May 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100521131137/http://volbeat.dk/2010/05/14/album-release-and-fall-dates-confirmed/ |archive-date=21 May 2010 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> In 2011, Volbeat announced their Grand Summer Tour across North America. The tour began in Toronto, Ontario on 24 July at Heavy T.O., and concluded with a two-night stand on 3 & 4 September at the House of Blues in Anaheim, CA. Volbeat co-headlined this tour with rock powerhouse [[Cold (band)|Cold]] on all US dates, but not in Canada. On 28 November 2011, Volbeat announced the departure of Bredahl via their website.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.volbeat.dk/2/news.php?id=70&lang=en |title=Under Construction |publisher=Volbeat.dk |accessdate=20 September 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120429015255/http://www.volbeat.dk/2/news.php?id=70&lang=en |archive-date=29 April 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Volbeat committed to playing all 2011-2012 as scheduled either as a trio, or with a replacement guitarist. On 26 January 2012, Volbeat joined [[Megadeth]], [[Mot\u00f6rhead]], and [[Lacuna Coil]] on [[Gigantour]]. The tour started in Camden, New Jersey and culminated on 28 February 2012 in Denver, CO at The Fillmore Auditorium. On the tour, [[Hank Shermann]] ([[Mercyful Fate]]) filled in as the guitarist for Volbeat. On their North American Summer tour, which began in June 2012, [[Iced Earth]] and [[Hellyeah]] were the supporting acts. The tour included dates in Baltimore, Toronto, Detroit, Billings, Boston, Tempe, San Francisco, and Weyburn and Lazerfest in Boone, IA and in June, Orion Music Festival, headlined by Metallica, at Bader Field in Atlantic City, New Jersey.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://lineup.orionmusicandmore.com/events/2012/06/23/ |title=Orion Music + More 2013 |publisher=Lineup.orionmusicandmore.com |accessdate=20 September 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130225102702/http://lineup.orionmusicandmore.com/events/2012/06/23/ |archive-date=25 February 2013 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\n===''Outlaw Gentlemen and Shady Ladies'' (2013\u20132016)===\n[[File:Volbeat 2013.jpg|thumb|left|Volbeat performing in 2013]]\nVolbeat were confirmed to be playing Download festival June 2013. Volbeat announced in December that their new album would be released during 2013. A spring tour with [[Danko Jones]] and [[Spoken (band)|Spoken]] was announced in December. In January 2013, Volbeat revealed the name of the new album, ''[[Outlaw Gentlemen & Shady Ladies]]'', and that was released in the spring of 2013.<ref name=\"allmusic1\"/>\n\nOn 4 February 2013, it was announced that Rob Caggiano, formerly of [[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]], had officially joined the band as second guitarist. He had been producing and recording guest solos on the band's upcoming album, ''Outlaw Gentlemen and Shady Ladies'', which the band also announced will be released on 8 April 2013 (GSA on 5 April and US on 9 April), before being asked to join as a full-time member. Singer and guitarist [[Michael Poulsen]] said of the chemistry between Caggiano and the rest of the band \"The collaboration with Rob in the studio was so inspiring and in good spirit that we the decided to keep him. Basically we went into the studio as a three piece and came out as a whole band!\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.volbeat.dk/2/news.php?id=98&lang=en |title=Under Construction |publisher=Volbeat.dk |accessdate=20 September 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130208043040/http://www.volbeat.dk/2/news.php?id=98&lang=en |archivedate=8 February 2013  }}</ref>\n\nMichael Poulsen confirmed during the band's 2015 tour with [[Anthrax (American band)|Anthrax]] and [[Crobot]], that a new album was in the works, hinting that it would be released in 2016, and demoed a new song throughout \"The Devil's Bleeding Crown\" tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/volbeat-performs-new-song-at-san-antonios-river-city-rockfest-video/ |title=Video: Volbeat Performs New Song |publisher=blabbermouth.net |date=25 May 2015 |accessdate=22 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, singer Poulsen revealed that he had so far written seven songs for the next album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bt.dk/musik/volbeat-interview-folk-tror-jeg-er-den-falske-michael-poulsen|title=Volbeat-interview: Folk tror, jeg er den falske Michael Poulsen|publisher=|accessdate=3 June 2016}}</ref> In November 2015, the band announced that Kj\u00f8lholm would leave Volbeat. They emphasised, that he left in good terms with the band. Poulsen and Larsen said that \"''Anders has been a loyal friend and bandmate since 2001.  [...] We're very thankful for this and wish Anders all the best in the future.''\" Kj\u00f8lholm likewise wished all the best for the rest of the band.<ref>[http://www.volbeat.dk/3/news/a-message-from-volbeat---44-.html A Message from Volbeat]. Volbeat.dk. Retrieved 14 November 2015</ref><ref>[http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/volbeat-parts-ways-with-bassist-anders-kjolholm/ Volbeat Parts Ways With Bassist Anders Kj\u00f8lholm]. [[Blabbermouth.net]]. Retrieved 9 December 2015</ref><ref>[http://gaffa.dk/nyhed/101316 Volbeat mister bassist]. ''[[Gaffa (magazine)|GAFFA]]''. Retrieved 9 December 2015</ref>\n\n===''Seal the Deal and Let's Boogie'' (2016\u20132017)===\nOn 3 April 2016, Volbeat posted a teaser for their upcoming album on YouTube, hinting it would be released soon. On 7 April 2016, they revealed ''Seal the Deal and Let's Boogie'' to be released on 3 June 2016. The album's first single was \"The Devil's Bleeding Crown\".<ref name = \"2016album\">{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/volbeat-to-release-seal-the-deal-listen-to-first-single-the-devils-bleeding-crown/|title=VOLBEAT's 'Seal The Deal & Let's Boogie' Album Due in June; Listen To 'The Devil's Bleeding Crown' Single |publisher=blabbermouth.net |date=7 April 2016|accessdate=8 April 2016}}</ref> The official music video for this song was released on 13 May 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/volbeat-devil-bleeding-crown-premiere/|title=Video Premiere: VOLBEAT's 'The Devil's Bleeding Crown'|date=13 May 2016|publisher=|accessdate=22 September 2017}}</ref> The second single, released 29 April 2016, was \"For Evigt\" (Forever), and an English version, \"The Bliss\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pasbani|first1=Robert|title=Volbeat Release Two Versions of Brand New Track \"The Bliss,\" So Catchy It Will Get Stuck In Your Head|url=http://www.metalinjection.net/latest-news/volbeat-release-two-versions-of-brand-new-track-the-bliss|accessdate=1 May 2017|work=Metal Injection|date=29 April 2016}}</ref> Kaspar Boye Larsen was announced as the band's new bassist on 13 May 2016.<ref>[http://www.volbeat.dk/en/news/new-video-volbeat-welcomes-new-bass----41-.html New Video + Volbeat Welcomes New Bass Player]. Volbeat. Retrieved 13 May 2016</ref> The band toured the United Kingdom in 2016 with [[Alter Bridge]], [[Gojira (band)|Gojira]], and [[Like a Storm]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rocksins.com/2016/07/alter-bridge-volbeat-gojira-like-storm-team-enormous-2016-uk-arena-tour-28094/|title=Alter Bridge Return To Headline UK Arenas On Nov 2016 Tour|website=Rocksins.com|accessdate=22 September 2017}}</ref> The band was an opening act on [[Metallica]]'s [[WorldWired Tour]] 2017 stadium tour in the US, alongside [[Avenged Sevenfold]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Metallica Announces 'WorldWired' North American Tour With Avenge Sevenfold And Volbeat|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/metallica-announces-worldwired-north-american-tour-with-avenged-sevenfold-and-volbeat/|accessdate=1 May 2017|work=Blabbermouth.net|date=13 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Hartmann|first1=Graham|title=Metallica Announce 2017 North American Tour With Avenged Sevenfold, Volbeat + Gojira |url=http://loudwire.com/metallica-2017-north-american-tour-avenged-sevenfold-volbeat-gojira/|accessdate=1 May 2017|work=Loudwire|date=13 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n===''Rewind, Replay, Rebound'' (2018\u2013present)===\nIn 2018, Volbeat announced plans for a seventh album.<ref>{{cite web |title=Volbeat's Next Album Will Have 'A Different Feel' From 'Seal The Deal & Let's Boogie' |url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/news/volbeats-next-album-will-have-a-different-feel-from-seal-the-deal-lets-boogie/ |website=Blabbermouth.net |accessdate=6 February 2019}}</ref> On 4 March 2019 Volbeat were announced, along with [[Gojira (band)|Gojira]] and [[Behemoth (band)|Behemoth]], as supporting acts for [[Slipknot (band)|Slipknot]]'s Knotfest Roadshow North American tour<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://loudwire.com/slipknot-volbeat-behemoth-gojira-tour/|title=Slipknot Announce Summer 2019 Tour With Volbeat, Behemoth, Gojira|last=Childers|first=Chad|website=Loudwire|access-date=4 March 2019}}</ref> On May 10, 2019, Volbeat released a 40-second song, \"Parasite\", and on May 15, they released the second single, \"Leviathan\", from their upcoming seventh studio album, ''Rewind, Replay, Rebound'', while announcing the 14-song tracklist and a release date of 2 August 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://loudwire.com/volbeat-rewind-replay-rebound-leviathan/|title=Volbeat Share New Album Details, Release \u2018Leviathan\u2019 Song|website=Loudwire|access-date=15 May 2019}}</ref> They released the third single off the album, \"Last Day Under the Sun\" on 13 June 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wallofsoundau.com/2019/06/14/volbert-announce-new-album-rewind-replay-rebound-drop-dad-rockin-new-song/|title=Volbeat Announce New Album \u2018Rewind, Replay, Rebound\u2019 + Drop Dad Rockin\u2019 New Song|date=13 June 2019|website=Wall of Sound|access-date=13 June 2019}}</ref> On 18 July 2019, the band released the fourth single, \"Cheapside Sloggers,\" featuring [[Gary Holt (musician)|Gary Holt]] of [[Slayer]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Kids take over for Volbeat in video for new song \u201cCheapside Sloggers\u201d featuring Slayer\u2019s Gary Holt: Watch|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2019/07/volbeat-new-song-cheapside-sloggers-slayer-gary-holt/|website=[[Consequence of Sound]]|accessdate=10 December 2019}}</ref> On 26 July 2019, the band released the fifth single, \"Pelvis on Fire.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Volbeat Channel Elvis on New Song 'Pelvis on Fire'|url=https://loudwire.com/volbeat-pelvis-on-fire/|website=[[Loudwire]]|accessdate=10 December 2019}}</ref> On 4 November 2019, the band released \"Die To Live,\" featuring [[Neil Fallon]] of [[Clutch (band)|Clutch]] as the sixth single.<ref>{{cite web |title=Hear Clutch\u2019s Neil Fallon Guest On New Volbeat Song \u201cDie To Live\u201d|url=https://www.theprp.com/2019/08/02/news/hear-clutchs-neil-fallon-guest-on-new-volbeat-song-die-to-live/|website=Theprp|accessdate=10 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n{{mainlist|List of awards and nominations received by Volbeat}}\n*''The Strength / The Sound / The Songs'' won the award for the best debut album at the Danish Metal Music Awards 2005.<ref name=dmeah>{{cite web |url=http://dmea.dk/dmea09/wp-content/uploads/DMeA_historik.pdf |title=DMeA Historik |publisher=DMEA.dk |date= |accessdate=20 February 2010 }}{{Dead link|date=July 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n*Volbeat won the award Steppeulven for hope of the year 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.steppeulv.dk |title=steppeulven |publisher=Steppeulv.dk |date= |accessdate=20 September 2013}}</ref>\n*Volbeat won the award for the best live band at the Danish Metal Music Awards 2006 voted by fans.<ref name=dmeah />\n*''Rock the Rebel / Metal the Devil'' won the award for best album at the Danish Metal Music Awards 2007.<ref name=dmeah />\n*Volbeat won the Danish radio award for P3 listener hit at the [[Danmarks Radio|P3 Guld-show]] voted by listeners of P3.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dr.dk/radio/p3|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202032935/http://www.dr.dk/P3/P3Guld/2007/nominerede/20061011094629.htm|url-status=dead|title=P3 Radio - Lyt til P3 live eller genh\u00f8r P3-programmer - P3 netradio &#124; DR Radio|archivedate=2 December 2008|website=Web.archive.org}}</ref>\n*Volbeat were nominated for the [[Grammy Award for Best Metal Performance]] for \"Room 24\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.grammy.com/grammys/awards|title=Awards Nominations & Winners|date=30 April 2017|website=Grammy.com}}</ref>\n\n==Musical style and influences==\nThe band's musical style has been described as [[Heavy metal music|heavy metal]],<ref name=\"lehighvalleylive\">{{cite web|first=Dustin|last=Schoof|url=https://www.lehighvalleylive.com/music/index.ssf/2014/04/volbeat_singer_discusses_fan_a.html|title=Volbeat singer discusses fan appreciation, influences and Young the Giant|date=25 April 2014|accessdate=3 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Toni|last=Ruberto|url=https://buffalonews.com/2017/03/20/volbeat-headlines-second-edgefest-show-at-artpark/|title=Volbeat headlines second Edgefest show at Artpark|publisher=Buffalo News|date=20 March 2017|accessdate=3 July 2018}}</ref> [[hard rock]],<ref name=\"lehighvalleylive\"/> [[psychobilly]],<ref>{{cite web|first=Chad|last=Vergine|url=https://nysmusic.com/2015/11/15/anders-kjolholm-parts-from-volbeat/|title=Anders Kj\u00f8lholm Parts From Volbeat|publisher=NYS Music|date=15 November 2015|accessdate=3 July 2018}}</ref> [[rockabilly]],<ref>{{cite web|first=Polly|last=Glass|url=https://www.loudersound.com/features/tracks-of-the-week-54|title=Tracks Of The Week: music and videos from Black Star Riders, Volbeat and more...|date=7 April 2017|accessdate=3 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"loudwire genres\">{{cite web|url=https://loudwire.com/volbeat-announce-2012-north-american-tour-dates-with-hellyeah/|title=Volbeat Announce 2012 North American Tour Dates With HellYeah|date=18 April 2012|accessdate=25 June 2019}}</ref> [[groove metal]],<ref name=\"loudwire genres\"/> and [[rock and roll]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.blabbermouth.net/cdreviews/the-strength-the-sound-the-songs/|title=The Strength/The Sound/The Songs - Volbeat|date=23 October 2005|newspaper=Blabbermouth.net|language=en-US|access-date=16 September 2019}}</ref> Chris True of [[AllMusic]] stated, \"[the band's] sound weds hard rock, classic metal, glam, [[Punk rock|punk]], and rockabilly.\"<ref name=\"allmusic1\"/> Some of the band's influences include [[Elvis Presley]], [[Johnny Cash]], [[Metallica]], [[AC/DC]], and [[Social Distortion]].<ref name=\"allmusic1\"/>\n\n==Band members==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-3}}\n'''Current members'''\n*[[Michael Poulsen]] \u2013 lead vocals, rhythm guitar <small>(2001\u2013present)</small>\n*[[Jon Larsen (Danish musician)|Jon Larsen]] \u2013 drums <small>(2001\u2013present)</small>\n*[[Rob Caggiano]] \u2013 lead guitar, backing vocals <small>(2013\u2013present)</small>, bass <small>(2015\u20132016)</small>\n*Kaspar Boye Larsen \u2013 bass, backing vocals <small>(2006, 2016\u2013present)</small>\n{{col-3}}\n'''Former members'''\n*[[Anders Kj\u00f8lholm]] \u2013 bass, backing vocals <small>(2001\u20132015)</small>\n*Teddy Vang \u2013 lead guitar <small>(2001\u20132002)</small>\n*[[Franz Gottschalk|Franz \"Hellboss\" Gottschalk]] \u2013 lead guitar, backing vocals <small>(2002\u20132006)</small>{{#tag:ref|''Rock the Rebel/Metal the Devil'' was released during Bredahl's tenure, but was recorded with Gottschalk on guitar.|group=\"nb\"}}\n*[[Thomas Bredahl]] \u2013 lead guitar, backing vocals <small>(2006\u20132011)</small>\n{{col-3}}\n'''Touring musicians'''\n*[[Hank Shermann]] \u2013 lead guitar <small>(2011\u20132013)</small>\n{{col-end}}\n'''Timeline'''\n{{#tag:timeline|\nImageSize = width:800 height:auto barincrement:20\nPlotArea = left:100 bottom:80 top:0 right:0\nAlignbars = justify\nDateFormat  = mm/dd/yyyy\nPeriod = from:01/01/2001 till:12/12/2019\nTimeAxis = orientation:horizontal format:yyyy\n\nColors =\n id:vocals  value:red    legend:Lead_vocals,_rhythm_guitar\n id:bvocals value:pink   legend:Backing_vocals\n id:guitar  value:green  legend:Lead_guitar\n id:bass    value:blue   legend:Bass\n id:drums   value:orange legend:Drums\n id:album   value:black  legend:Studio_album\n\nLegend = orientation:horizontal position:bottom\n\nScaleMajor = increment:2 start:2001\nScaleMinor = increment:1 start:2001\n\nLineData =\n layer:back\n  color:album\n   at:09/26/2005 \n   at:02/26/2007\n   at:09/01/2008\n   at:09/10/2010\n   