[[New York (state)|New York]].<ref name=\"Farley\">{{cite news |last1=Farley |first1=Henry G. |title=Robert Packer Hospital 130th Anniversary |url=https://www.guthrie.org/sites/default/files/pictures/Farley%20Historic%20Article%20with%20Photos.pdf |accessdate=17 May 2019 |publisher=Guthrie |date=March 2015}}</ref> The hospital is a primary [[stroke]] center and level II [[trauma center]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.stargazette.com/story/news/local/2016/09/29/guthrie-hospital-earns-national-stroke-accreditation/91283754/ |title=Guthrie hospital earns national stroke accreditation |date=29 Sep 2016 |work=Elmira Star-Gazette |access-date=23 May 2019 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=PA Trauma Systems Foundation |url=http://ptsf.org/our-trauma-centers/trauma-centers |website=ptsf.org |accessdate=23 May 2019}}</ref> It has received numerous awards, including being named one of the Truven Top 50 Cardiovascular Hospitals 10 times since 2001, \"America\u2019s 100 Best Hospitals for [[Interventional cardiology|Coronary Intervention]]\" by HealthGrades in 2017, 2018, and 2019 and receiving a [[Bariatric Surgery]] Excellence Award in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=50 Top Cardiovascular > Winners Through the Years |url=http://truvenhealth.com/Products/100-Top-Hospitals/Program-Info/50-Top-Cardiovascular/Winners-Through-the-Years |website=truvenhealth.com |accessdate=23 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Guthrie Robert Packer Hospital - Sayre, PA |url=https://www.healthgrades.com/hospital-directory/pennsylvania-pa/guthrie-robert-packer-hospital-hgst6069e6a6390079 |accessdate=23 May 2019 |work=www.healthgrades.com |publisher=Healthgrades}}</ref> It has also received a Center of Distinction Award for [[wound care]] and [[Hyperbaric medicine|hyperbarics]] in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |title=2018 Center of Distinction Winners {{!}} Healogics |url=http://www.healogics.com/2018-Center-of-Distinction-Winners |website=www.healogics.com}}</ref>\n\n== Early history ==\nRobert Asa Packer, son of [[Asa Packer]], was a business magnate and president of the Northern Division of the [[Lehigh Valley Railroad]].<ref name=\"Himedo\">{{cite web |title=Robert Asa Packer |url=https://himedo.net/TheHopkinThomasProject/FamilyTies/BiographicalData/ps01/ps01_453.htm |website=himedo.net}}</ref> After his death in 1883, his mansion (built 1879-80) sat empty and was inherited by his sister, Mary Packer Cummings. She was approached by Rev. W. B. Morrow, the rector of the Church of the Redeemer, with plans for a hospital and she donated the home to the Lehigh Valley Railroad Company on February 14, 1885 to be used for that purpose.<ref name=\"Charitable\" /><ref>{{cite book |last1=Wilcox |first1=Elizabeth G. |title=Sayre and Early Valley History |date=1958 |publisher=Elizabeth G. Wilcox |location=Philadelphia |url=https://archive.org/details/sayreearlyvalley00wilc}}</ref> She also offered to pay for any required alterations.<ref name=Farley2 /> In turn, a corporation formed for the care of \"injured and sick persons without distinction on account of creed, race, or nationality,\" and a charter was granted for the hospital one month later on March 16.<ref name=\"Bradsby\">{{cite book |last1=Bradsby |first1=H. C. |title=History of Bradford County, Pennsylvania, with biographical selections. |date=1891 |publisher=S. B. Nelson |location=Chicago |url=https://catalog.hathitrust.org/Record/011262513}}</ref><ref name=Farley />\n\nRobert Packer Hospital was dedicated on July 13, 1885, the house surgeon being Dr. Franklin M. Stephens, with the first patient, Alonzo House, arriving two weeks later.<ref name=Farley /> The majority of the patients in the first years were injured while working for the Lehigh Valley Railroad and Sayre Locomotive Shops.<ref name=\"Charitable\">{{cite book |title=Charitable Institutions of Pennsylvania which Have Received State Aid in 1897 and 1898 |date=1898 |publisher=Pennsylvania Office of the Auditor General |pages=343\u2013347 |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Charitable_Institutions_of_Pennsylvania.html?id=ATTJAAAAMAAJ |accessdate=17 May 2019}}</ref> The hospital was known for its use of aseptic techniques, only resorting to amputation for infection once in the first five years. Despite the fact that patients generally feared hospitals, in 1893 and 1894 that the hospital often went over capacity and had to turn away admissions. Some patients would wait weeks for admission.<ref name=\"Charitable\" />\n\nEarly on, money was set aside for repairs to the old building and construction of a new ward, but it turned out not to be enough. Despite rarely having vacant beds, the hospital still went further into debt, largely due to not charging patients for their care.<ref name=\"Charitable\" />\n\n== History after Dr. Guthrie's arrival ==\nJanuary 10, 1910, [[Donald Guthrie (physician)|Dr. Donald Guthrie]] succeeded the surgeon-in-chief Dr. Ott, who had died the year prior.<ref name=Farley /><ref name=Farley2 /> He founded the Guthrie Medical Group and expanded services in the hospital to model it after the [[Mayo Clinic]], where he had completed his residency.<ref name=official /> In 1912, Mary Packer Cummings died and willed funds to build a children's ward.<ref name=Farley2 /> By 1920, Dr. Guthrie had added 11 more physicians to the group. Only eight years later, the four story Guthrie Clinic building opened with 27 physicians.<ref name=\"100years\">{{cite book |title=Guthrie: 100 Years of Health Care |date=2010 |publisher=Arcadia Publishing |location=Charleston, SC |isbn=978-0738572215}}</ref>\n\nThe hospital and its buildings were considered to be some of the most advanced in the country. In September, 1916, Ornan H. Waltz noted in ''Modern Hospital,'' \"Sayre, Pa., a city of only eight thousand people, can boast of one of the most serviceable institutions in the country[.]\"<ref name=\"ModernHospital\">{{Cite journal |last=Waltz |first=Ornan H. |date=Sep 1916 |title=Private Room Building of the Robert Packer Hospital |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fDchAQAAMAAJ&pg=PA198 |journal=Modern Hospital |volume=7 |pages=198-201}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Robert Packer Hospital Reconstruction.jpg|thumb|left|Robert Packer Hospital, ca. 1934]]\nA major portion of the hospital burned down in a fire on May 3, 1933, forcing the hospital administration to successfully raise funds for a larger updated building for which they had been planning since 1929.<ref name=\"HVFM2018\">{{cite web |title=Heritage Village and Farm Museum Guide 2018 Edition |url=http://mansfieldpennysaver.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/02/HVFM-GUIDE-2018.pdf |website=Mansfield Pennysaver |publisher=The Bradford County Heritage Association |accessdate=29 May 2019}}</ref> At the time, some of the patients were moved to Tioga County General Hospital.<ref name=100years /><ref>{{cite news |title=The Robert Packer Hospital Fire |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4031744/rph_fire/ |accessdate=23 May 2019 |work=The Evening Times |date=4 May 1933 |language=en}}</ref> The hospital received a Public Works Administration loan in the amount of $420,000 to complete the new building meant to house 285 beds, which was opened on December 6, 1934.<ref name=\"Farley2\">{{cite news |last1=Farley |first1=Henry G. |title=Celebrating 125 years: A History of Robert Packer Hospital |url=https://www.thetimes-tribune.com/celebrating-125-years-a-history-of-robert-packer-hospital-1.695616 |accessdate=23 May 2019 |work=Scranton Times-Tribune |date=22 Mar 2010}}</ref>\n\nMultiple changes have taken place since then, including addition of new buildings, operating suites, educational buildings, and an emergency department. 1981 saw the formation of the Guthrie Medical Center, a new corporation and restructuring of the existing Guthrie Clinic. In 1986, the hospital switched its focus to taking care of trauma patients, adding an $85,000 heliport, establishing trauma-related hospital procedures, and bringing in appropriate staffing.<ref name=Farley2 />\n\n== Education ==\nRobert Packer Hospital had its first intern in 1887, at a time when most physicians did not do internships. Its first residency began in 1923 in partnership with the [[Perelman School of Medicine|University of Pennsylvania Graduate School of Medicine]], and was in general surgery. Five years later, a residency in medicine was added.<ref name=\"GuthrieRes\">{{cite web |title=Guthrie Residency Programs: Then and Now |url=https://www.guthrie.org/guthrie-residency-programs-then-and-now |website=www.guthrie.org |publisher=Guthrie |accessdate=23 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe hospital employed its first Director of Medical Education in 1967, also breaking ground for the Carl V. S. Patterson Education Building. The same year, the School of Nursing was accredited by the [[National League for Nursing]]. In 1987, nursing education changed at Robert Packer Hospital and it no longer offered a diploma program. Instead, it partnered with [[Mansfield University]] in offering the [[Bachelor of Science in Nursing]] degree.<ref name=Farley2 />\n\nAs of May 2019, the hospital has physician [[Residency (medicine)|residencies]] in [[emergency medicine]], [[family medicine]], [[general surgery]], [[internal medicine]] and fellowships in [[cardiology]], [[gastroenterology]], and [[pulmonology]] and [[Intensive care medicine|critical care]]. Additionally, the hospital has a nurse residency, [[pharmacy residency]], and is the Guthrie Campus of the [[Geisinger Commonwealth School of Medicine]].<ref name=official /><ref>{{cite web |title=Guthrie Campus (Sayre) |url=https://www.geisinger.edu/education/regional-campuses/guthrie-campus-sayre |website=www.geisinger.edu |publisher=Geisinger Commonwealth School of Medicine |accessdate=23 May 2019 |language=en}}</ref> Of historical note, it used to have residencies in anesthesiology, neurosurgery, orthopedic surgery, pathology, pediatrics, radiology, and urology.<ref name=Farley2 />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Guthrie}}\n{{Pennsylvania Trauma Centers}}\n\n[[Category:Teaching hospitals in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1885]]\n[[Category:1885 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Sayre, Pennsylvania]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Guthrie_Robert_Packer_Hospital"}
{"title_page": "Guthrie Cortland Medical Center", "text_new": "{{Infobox hospital\n<!-- All parameters and comments should be left intact for future editors -->\n<!-- All parameters are optional, but please copy the entire template -->\n<!-- Full documentation: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Infobox_hospital -->\n| name        = Guthrie Cortland Medical Center\n| org/group   = Guthrie<!-- org or group that owns/manages the hospital -->\n| logo        = Guthrie_logo.svg<!-- please conform to copyright -->\n| logo_size   = <!-- logo size or width in pixels -->\n| image       = <!-- preferably photo of the main building or entrance -->\n| image_size  = <!-- 220 is the default image size or width in pixels (225 matches default map_size). Leave blank per [[MOS:ACCESSIBILITY]] unless special size is needed. -->\n| alt         = <!-- alternative text for image, see [[WP:ALT]] -->\n| caption     = <!-- text displayed below image -->\n| map_type    = <!-- uses the [[Template:Location map]] format; defines value for {{{1}}} parameter; must have latitude and longitude if using this -->\n| relief      = <!-- any non-blank value (yes, 1, etc.) will cause the template to display a relief map image, where available -->\n| map_size    = <!-- map size or width in pixels (do not include \"px\"); default is 225 -->\n| map_alt     = <!-- alternative text for map image, see WP:ALT for details -->\n| map_caption = <!-- a small caption under the map such as \"Shown in region, country\" -->\n| mapframe-zoom = 5\n| location    = 134 Homer Avenue<!-- optional \u2013 displayed before region, state, country -->\n| region      = [[Cortland, New York|Cortland]]<!-- e.g. City or County -->\n| state       = [[New York (state)|New York]]<!-- optional \u2013 UK: England, Wales, Scotland, Northern Ireland; US: the US state name; CA: province name -->\n| country     = US<!-- country name or two-letter code \u2013 use UK for United Kingdom or US for United States -->\n| coordinates = {{coord|42|36|31.7|N|76|11|15.0|W|display=inline, title}}<!-- Use {{coord}} template with 'display=inline, title' -->\n| healthcare  = Private<!-- UK: NHS; AU/CA: Medicare; ELSE free-form text, e.g. Private -->\n| funding     = Non-profit<!-- use: Non-profit, For-profit, Government, Public \u2013 will generate links -->\n| type        = Community<!-- use: Community, District, General, District General, Teaching, Specialist -->\n| religious_affiliation = <!-- religion the hospital is associated with -->\n| affiliation = <!-- medical school / university affiliations (medical or paramedical) -->\n| patron      = <!-- the individual who acts as the hospital patron -->\n| network     = <!-- hospital network, non-owner -->\n| standards   = <!-- optional if no national standards -->\n| emergency   = <!-- UK/IR/HK/SG: Yes/No, in CA/IL/US: I/II/III/IV/V for Trauma certification level -->\n| beds        = 144<!-- cite in article as well -->\n| speciality  = <!-- if devoted to a speciality (i.e. not a broad spectrum); ONLY displayed if type=Specialist or type=Teaching -->\n| helipad     = <!-- [[Template:Airport codes]] with p=n; leave blank if unknown or not verifiable -->\n| h1-number   = <!-- The designation of the helipad (up to h12) -->\n| h1-length-f = <!-- Helipad length in feet -->\n| h1-length-m = <!-- Helipad length in metres -->\n| h1-surface  = <!-- Helipad surface type, such as: Concrete, Asphalt, etc -->\n| founded     = 1891<!-- cite in article as well -->\n| closed      = <!-- if defunct, please also add to Category:Defunct hospitals -->\n| demolished  = <!-- if demolished at a different time from closure -->\n| website     = {{URL|www.guthrie.org/location/guthrie-cortland-medical-center}}\n| other_links = <!-- link(s) to related articles -->\n| module      = <!-- or 'embedded' or 'nrhp' -->\n}}\nThe '''Guthrie Cortland Medical Center''', formerly known as '''Cortland Regional Medical Center,''' is a large [[rural]] [[hospital]] in [[Cortland, New York]] founded in 1891.<ref name=\"benevolent\">{{cite book |last1=United States Bureau of the Census |last2=Koren |first2=John |last3=King |first3=William Alexander |title=Benevolent institutions 1904 |date=1905 |publisher=Govt. Print. Off. |url=https://archive.org/details/benevolentinsti00censgoog |page=[https://archive.org/details/benevolentinsti00censgoog/page/n304 313] |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"USN\">{{cite web |title=Cortland Regional Medical Center |url=https://health.usnews.com/best-hospitals/area/ny/cortland-regional-medical-center-6211370 |website=U.S. News Health |publisher=U.S. News |accessdate=30 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Official\">{{cite web |title=Guthrie Cortland Medical Center, NY |url=https://www.guthrie.org/location/guthrie-cortland-medical-center |website=www.guthrie.org |publisher=Guthrie |accessdate=30 May 2019}}</ref> Cortland Regional Medical Center was ranked the top hospital in New York State by [[Centers for Medicare and Medicaid]] in 2015 and 2017.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cortland Regional ranked number one NY hospital in new federal health care ranking |url=https://cortlandvoice.com/2017/11/10/cortland-regional-ranked-number-one-ny-hospital-new-federal-health-care-ranking/ |accessdate=30 May 2019 |work=Cortland Voice |date=10 November 2017}}</ref> In 2016, it was received the Blue Distinction Center+ for Maternity Care award.<ref name=Official />\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Cortland Hospital c1906 postcard.jpg|thumb|left|Cortland Hospital circa 1906]]\nOctober 22, 1888 saw the formation of Cortland's [[International Order of the King's Daughters and Sons|Loyal Circle of King's Daughters]]. Rev. J. A. Robinson, of Grace Church, had been recommending the formation of a hospital for the region, and the King's Daughters decided to make this the first major order of business. By April of the next year, $25 was set aside. In February, 1891, a public meeting was held to discuss the organization of a hospital and ten days later, on February 23, 1891, the Cortland Hospital Association was formed. The King's Daughters transferred $1300 to the new organization's treasury.<ref name=Grips>{{cite book |last1=Welch |first1=Edgar Luderne |title=\"Grip's\" Historical Souvenir of Cortland |date=1899 |location=Cortland, NY |pages=[https://archive.org/details/gripshistoricals00we/page/26 26]-27 |url=https://archive.org/details/gripshistoricals00we |language=en}}</ref>\n\nCortland Hospital, with space for six patients, opened on April 1, 1891 in a rented cottage on Clayton Avenue. Within just a few short years, the number of patients outgrew this hospital and an 1834 home at 84 North Main Street was bought for $6000 and dedicated on March 27, 1895.<ref name=Arcadia /> It had five private patient rooms, two [[Hospital ward|wards]] with seven beds each, and a classroom for nurse training, with room to expand to 25 beds if needed.<ref name=Grips /><ref name=Official /><ref name=Seq>{{cite book |title=Cortland County Sesquicentennial Celebration, July 20-26, 1958: Souvenir Book |date=1958 |location=Cortland, NY |pages=16\u201318 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HsPTAAAAMAAJ |language=en}}</ref> The previous year, in 1894, a training program for nurses was started.<ref name=Official /><ref>{{cite book |last1=Hodson |first1=Jane |title=How to become a trained nurse : a manual of information in detail ; with a complete list of the various training schools for nurses in the United States and Canada |date=1898 |publisher=William Abbatt |location=New York |page=[https://archive.org/details/39002011210714.med.yale.edu/page/175 175] |url=https://archive.org/details/39002011210714.med.yale.edu}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Cortland Hospital c1911 postcard.jpg|thumb|Cortland Hospital circa 1911]]\n[[File:Cortland Hospital c1913 postcard.jpg|thumb|Cortland Hospital circa 1913]]\nAround 1909, George H. Wiltsie sold his five-acre property at 134 Homer Avenue to the hospital association for $18,000 and Chester F. Wickwire initially donated $70,000 to construct a \"first-rate\" facility. The property housed the Copeland-Fitz Boynton residence which was attached to the rear of the new building. This Cortland Hospital opened in 1911 with an entrance modeled on that of the [[White House]]. By 1911, Wickwire had donated a total of $95,000.<ref name=Official /><ref name=Arcadia>{{cite book |last1=Kane |first1=Mary Ann |title=Cortland |date=2010 |publisher=Arcadia Publishing |location=Charleston, SC |isbn=9780738573045 |pages=21, 39\u201340, 51, 70 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KJ1a0Daa0NkC |language=en}}</ref> The new hospital had 52 beds total with separate wards for men and women, 22 private rooms, a children's ward, and two [[operating rooms]].<ref name=Official />\n\nCortland Hospital opened a new 21-bed maternity wing in February 1922, delivering 135 babies by the end of the year. Six years later, the hospital expands again, adding a west pavilion that brought the hospital's total beds to 115.<ref name=Official />\n\nIn 1946, the [[SUNY Cortland|University of the State of New York]] opened a [[nursing school]] in [[Morrisville, New York]] and Cortland County Hospital became a clinical training site. This partnership existed until 1980.<ref name=Official />\n\nCortland expanded again in 1962, opening a central pavilion that expanded the hospital to 170 beds. All open wards were closed by 1966, with patients in private and semi-private rooms. In 1978, a new south wing was completed with two new 33-bed medical-surgical units, a new [[intensive care unit]] and [[pediatrics]] units, a new [[emergency department]], laboratory, and [[radiology]] department.<ref name=Official/>\n\nIn 1993, the hospital opened a new 80 bed [[nursing home]]. Ten years later, a new emergency department and [[urgent care]] were opened.\n\nOver the years and multiple changes, the name has changed from Cortland Hospital, to Cortland County Hospital (1917), Cortland Memorial Hospital (1955), to Cortland Regional Medical Center (2006), and most recently, Guthrie Cortland Medical Center when it became an entity of the [[Guthrie Robert Packer Hospital|Guthrie Clinic]] January 1, 2019.<ref name=Arcadia /><ref name=Official /> Guthrie is now its [[parent organization]] after Cortland had mounting financial losses and patient number decline.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mulder |first1=James T. |title=Guthrie Clinic of Pennsylvania comes to rescue Cortland hospital |url=https://www.syracuse.com/news/2018/10/guthrie_clinic_of_pennylvania_comes_to_rescue_cortland_hospital.html |accessdate=31 May 2019 |work=syracuse.com |date=12 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\nIn 2015, the [[Leapfrog Group]] rated Cortland Regional Medical Center \"F\" for patient safety, one of only two hospitals in New York to receive this grade.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McCaughey |first1=Betsy |title=New York\u2019s most dangerous hospitals |url=https://nypost.com/2015/05/10/new-yorks-most-dangerous-hospitals/ |work=New York Post |date=11 May 2015 |language=en}}</ref> By spring 2019, the hospital has consistently raised its grade to \"C.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Guthrie Cortland Medical Center - NY - Hospital Safety Grade |url=https://www.hospitalsafetygrade.org/h/guthrie-cortland-medical-center |website=www.hospitalsafetygrade.org |publisher=Leapfrog Group |accessdate=30 May 2019 |language=en}}</ref> The [[New York State Department of Health]] rated the hospital with all average and above average ratings in the same categories for 2018.<ref name=NYS>{{cite web |title=NYS Health Profile: Guthrie Cortland Medical Center |url=https://profiles.health.ny.gov/hospital/view/102996 |website=profiles.health.ny.gov |publisher=NYS Dept. of Health |accessdate=30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Guthrie}}\n\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1891]]\n[[Category:1891 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Cortland County, New York]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in New York (state)]]\n{{authority control}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox hospital\n<!-- All parameters and comments should be left intact for future editors -->\n<!-- All parameters are optional, but please copy the entire template -->\n<!-- Full documentation: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Infobox_hospital -->\n| name        = Guthrie Cortland Medical Center\n| org/group   = Guthrie<!-- org or group that owns/manages the hospital -->\n| logo        = Guthrie_logo.svg<!-- please conform to copyright -->\n| logo_size   = <!-- logo size or width in pixels -->\n| image       = <!-- preferably photo of the main building or entrance -->\n| image_size  = <!-- 220 is the default image size or width in pixels (225 matches default map_size). Leave blank per [[MOS:ACCESSIBILITY]] unless special size is needed. -->\n| alt         = <!-- alternative text for image, see [[WP:ALT]] -->\n| caption     = <!-- text displayed below image -->\n| map_type    = <!-- uses the [[Template:Location map]] format; defines value for {{{1}}} parameter; must have latitude and longitude if using this -->\n| relief      = <!-- any non-blank value (yes, 1, etc.) will cause the template to display a relief map image, where available -->\n| map_size    = <!-- map size or width in pixels (do not include \"px\"); default is 225 -->\n| map_alt     = <!-- alternative text for map image, see WP:ALT for details -->\n| map_caption = <!-- a small caption under the map such as \"Shown in region, country\" -->\n| mapframe-zoom = 5\n| location    = 134 Homer Avenue<!-- optional \u2013 displayed before region, state, country -->\n| region      = [[Cortland, New York|Cortland]]<!-- e.g. City or County -->\n| state       = [[New York (state)|New York]]<!-- optional \u2013 UK: England, Wales, Scotland, Northern Ireland; US: the US state name; CA: province name -->\n| country     = US<!-- country name or two-letter code \u2013 use UK for United Kingdom or US for United States -->\n| coordinates = {{coord|42|36|31.7|N|76|11|15.0|W|display=inline, tit