=United States Bureau of the Census |last2=Koren |first2=John |last3=King |first3=William Alexander |title=Benevolent institutions 1904 |date=1905 |publisher=Govt. Print. Off. |url=https://archive.org/details/benevolentinsti00censgoog |page=[https://archive.org/details/benevolentinsti00censgoog/page/n304 313] |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"USN\">{{cite web |title=Cortland Regional Medical Center |url=https://health.usnews.com/best-hospitals/area/ny/cortland-regional-medical-center-6211370 |website=U.S. News Health |publisher=U.S. News |accessdate=30 May 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Official\">{{cite web |title=Guthrie Cortland Medical Center, NY |url=https://www.guthrie.org/location/guthrie-cortland-medical-center |website=www.guthrie.org |publisher=Guthrie |accessdate=30 May 2019}}</ref> Cortland Regional Medical Center was ranked the top hospital in New York State by [[Centers for Medicare and Medicaid]] in 2015 and 2017.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cortland Regional ranked number one NY hospital in new federal health care ranking |url=https://cortlandvoice.com/2017/11/10/cortland-regional-ranked-number-one-ny-hospital-new-federal-health-care-ranking/ |accessdate=30 May 2019 |work=Cortland Voice |date=10 November 2017}}</ref> In 2016, it was received the Blue Distinction Center+ for Maternity Care award.<ref name=Official />\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Cortland Hospital c1906 postcard.jpg|thumb|left|Cortland Hospital circa 1906]]\nOctober 22, 1888 saw the formation of Cortland's [[International Order of the King's Daughters and Sons|Loyal Circle of King's Daughters]]. Rev. J. A. Robinson, of Grace Church, had been recommending the formation of a hospital for the region, and the King's Daughters decided to make this the first major order of business. By April of the next year, $25 was set aside. In February, 1891, a public meeting was held to discuss the organization of a hospital and ten days later, on February 23, 1891, the Cortland Hospital Association was formed. The King's Daughters transferred $1300 to the new organization's treasury.<ref name=Grips>{{cite book |last1=Welch |first1=Edgar Luderne |title=\"Grip's\" Historical Souvenir of Cortland |date=1899 |location=Cortland, NY |pages=[https://archive.org/details/gripshistoricals00we/page/26 26]-27 |url=https://archive.org/details/gripshistoricals00we |language=en}}</ref>\n\nCortland Hospital, with space for six patients, opened on April 1, 1891 in a rented cottage on Clayton Avenue. Within just a few short years, the number of patients outgrew this hospital and an 1834 home at 84 North Main Street was bought for $6000 and dedicated on March 27, 1895.<ref name=Arcadia /> It had five private patient rooms, two [[Hospital ward|wards]] with seven beds each, and a classroom for nurse training, with room to expand to 25 beds if needed.<ref name=Grips /><ref name=Official /><ref name=Seq>{{cite book |title=Cortland County Sesquicentennial Celebration, July 20-26, 1958: Souvenir Book |date=1958 |location=Cortland, NY |pages=16-18 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HsPTAAAAMAAJ |language=en}}</ref> The previous year, in 1894, a training program for nurses was started.<ref name=Official /><ref>{{cite book |last1=Hodson |first1=Jane |title=How to become a trained nurse : a manual of information in detail ; with a complete list of the various training schools for nurses in the United States and Canada |date=1898 |publisher=William Abbatt |location=New York |page=[https://archive.org/details/39002011210714.med.yale.edu/page/175 175] |url=https://archive.org/details/39002011210714.med.yale.edu}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Cortland Hospital c1911 postcard.jpg|thumb|Cortland Hospital circa 1911]]\n[[File:Cortland Hospital c1913 postcard.jpg|thumb|Cortland Hospital circa 1913]]\nAround 1909, George H. Wiltsie sold his five-acre property at 134 Homer Avenue to the hospital association for $18,000 and Chester F. Wickwire initially donated $70,000 to construct a \"first-rate\" facility. The property housed the Copeland-Fitz Boynton residence which was attached to the rear of the new building. This Cortland Hospital opened in 1911 with an entrance modeled on that of the [[White House]]. By 1911, Wickwire had donated a total of $95,000.<ref name=Official /><ref name=Arcadia>{{cite book |last1=Kane |first1=Mary Ann |title=Cortland |date=2010 |publisher=Arcadia Publishing |location=Charleston, SC |isbn=9780738573045 |pages=21, 39-40, 51, 70 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KJ1a0Daa0NkC |language=en}}</ref> The new hospital had 52 beds total with separate wards for men and women, 22 private rooms, a children's ward, and two [[operating rooms]].<ref name=Official />\n\nCortland Hospital opened a new 21-bed maternity wing in February 1922, delivering 135 babies by the end of the year. Six years later, the hospital expands again, adding a west pavilion that brought the hospital's total beds to 115.<ref name=Official />\n\nIn 1946, the [[SUNY Cortland|University of the State of New York]] opened a [[nursing school]] in [[Morrisville, New York]] and Cortland County Hospital became a clinical training site. This partnership existed until 1980.<ref name=Official />\n\nCortland expanded again in 1962, opening a central pavilion that expanded the hospital to 170 beds. All open wards were closed by 1966, with patients in private and semi-private rooms. In 1978, a new south wing was completed with two new 33-bed medical-surgical units, a new [[intensive care unit]] and [[pediatrics]] units, a new [[emergency department]], laboratory, and [[radiology]] department.<ref name=Official/>\n\nIn 1993, the hospital opened a new 80 bed [[nursing home]]. Ten years later, a new emergency department and [[urgent care]] were opened.\n\nOver the years and multiple changes, the name has changed from Cortland Hospital, to Cortland County Hospital (1917), Cortland Memorial Hospital (1955), to Cortland Regional Medical Center (2006), and most recently, Guthrie Cortland Medical Center when it became an entity of the [[Guthrie Robert Packer Hospital|Guthrie Clinic]] January 1, 2019.<ref name=Arcadia /><ref name=Official /> Guthrie is now its [[parent organization]] after Cortland had mounting financial losses and patient number decline.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Mulder |first1=James T. |title=Guthrie Clinic of Pennsylvania comes to rescue Cortland hospital |url=https://www.syracuse.com/news/2018/10/guthrie_clinic_of_pennylvania_comes_to_rescue_cortland_hospital.html |accessdate=31 May 2019 |work=syracuse.com |date=12 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Controversies ==\nIn 2015, the [[Leapfrog Group]] rated Cortland Regional Medical Center \"F\" for patient safety, one of only two hospitals in New York to receive this grade.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McCaughey |first1=Betsy |title=New York\u2019s most dangerous hospitals |url=https://nypost.com/2015/05/10/new-yorks-most-dangerous-hospitals/ |work=New York Post |date=11 May 2015 |language=en}}</ref> By spring 2019, the hospital has consistently raised its grade to \"C.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Guthrie Cortland Medical Center - NY - Hospital Safety Grade |url=https://www.hospitalsafetygrade.org/h/guthrie-cortland-medical-center |website=www.hospitalsafetygrade.org |publisher=Leapfrog Group |accessdate=30 May 2019 |language=en}}</ref> The [[New York State Department of Health]] rated the hospital with all average and above average ratings in the same categories for 2018.<ref name=NYS>{{cite web |title=NYS Health Profile: Guthrie Cortland Medical Center |url=https://profiles.health.ny.gov/hospital/view/102996 |website=profiles.health.ny.gov |publisher=NYS Dept. of Health |accessdate=30 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Guthrie}}\n\n[[Category:Hospitals established in 1891]]\n[[Category:1891 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Cortland County, New York]]\n[[Category:Hospitals in New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": 